Enzootic abortion of ewes (ovine chlamydiosis), Tunisia

Information received on 16 Mar 2012 from Dr Abdelhak Benyounes, Directeur general des services veterinaires, Direction generale des services veterinaires, Ministere de l'agriculture et de l'environnement, Tunis, Tunisia

Summary
Report type Immediate notification (Final report)
Start date 22 Dec 2011
Date of 1st confirmation of the event 06 Jan 2012
Report date 16 Mar 2012
Date submitted to OIE 16 Mar 2012
Date event resolved 15 Mar 2012
Reason for notification Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence March 2006
Manifestation of disease Clinical disease
Causal agent Chlamydophila abortus
Nature of diagnosis Clinical, Laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1 Om elferth, Saiden, Kebili nord, Kebili
Date of start of the outbreak 22 Dec 2011
Outbreak status Resolved (15 Mar 2012)
Epidemiological unit Farm
Species Goats
Susceptible 74
Cases 6
Deaths 0
Destroyed 0
Slaughtered 6

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection
Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: It is the same animal population from which samples were taken for Q fever (see also immediate notification on 16 March 2012) and chlamydiosis.

Control measures
Measures applied
Disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s)
Vaccination prohibited
Treatment of affected animals (treatment with broad-spectrum
antibiotics to treat the double infection (coxielosis and chlamydiosis) )
Measures to be applied
No other measures

Future Reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-Mail
promed@promedmail.org

[There are a couple of unusual items in this report. First, this is a report of dual infection with 2 separate notifiable infections in the same population. Not only is this mentioned in the epidemiologic comments but there is the same number of goats in the same location in both reports. The reports were filed as separate OIE immediate notifications but cross referenced in the Epidemiologic comments section. They have been combined in one posting for the convenience of our readers.

The other unusual item in these reports is that neither one includes information on how the diagnosis was made, although both refer to clinical and basic laboratory information under the "Nature of diagnosis" section of the report. A previous OIE report indicates a PCR finding for Q fever - see references below for Q fever - Netherlands (20): goats, OIE 20091230.4388. - Mod.PC

Location of Kebili in Tunisia on ProMEDmail/Healthmap is available at: http//healthmap.org/r/1*kj: - Mod.FE]
